    "created_at": "2014-10-21T22:29:34Z",
    "updated_at": "2014-10-21T22:29:34Z",
    "body": "@arielb1: There is absolutely no guarantee of a segfault when dereferencing a null pointer. It only causes that on a subset of platforms due to the zero page being mapped as PROT_NONE. The use case for `#![no_std]` includes use cases like a kernel where it is _not common_ for this to result in a deterministic crash. It's dangerous undefined behaviour and can be exploited as a memory corruption vulnerability. \n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
